{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"226985e5-c173-415e-9d52-6fcd7593b2f6","content":"## What's happening\n\n**.NET 11 likely raised the x86-64 Linux baseline to x86-64-v3**, which requires **AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, FMA**, and other instructions only available starting with Intel **Haswell (2013)** / AMD **Excavator (2015)**. (.NET 9 previously raised it from v1 to v2.)\n\nYour 2012-era hardware is probably **Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge** — these have AVX but **not AVX2**, so they fail the v3 baseline check at startup.\n\n## Your other targets are fine\n\n| Target | Why it works |\n|---|---|\n| **Windows Arm64** (SQ1) | ARM baseline is separate; unaffected by x86 changes |\n| **Raspberry Pi 4** (Linux ARM64) | Same — ARM architecture, no x86 baseline applies |\n\n## Options\n\n1. **Retire the 2012 hardware** — replace with Haswell-era (2013+) or newer\n2. **Stay on .NET 10 LTS** for those specific nodes while upgrading the rest\n3. **Check for a compat switch** — .NET 9 offered `DOTNET_EnableSSE3=0`-style knobs initially; see if .NET 11 offers a v2-fallback option (unlikely for production support)\n\nYou can verify the failing node's CPU capabilities with:\n\n```bash\ngrep -m1 'model name' /proc/cpuinfo\ngrep -oP 'avx2' /proc/cpuinfo | head -1\n```\n\nIf `avx2` is missing, that confirms the diagnosis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a459859d-9491-4c4c-95ac-81b3ae78b9c1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly without needing tools.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. However, looking more carefully, the actual change was:\n\n- .NET 8 and earlier: x86-64 baseline (SSE, SSE2)\n\n\n- .NET 9+: x86-64-v2 baseline on Linux (requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, CMPXCHG16B)\n\nBut wait, if they were already running .NET 10, they should have already hit this requirement. Let me think about whether .NET 11 introduces an additional constraint or if something else is going on here. , which those older CPUs wouldn't have. So if the user's 2012 hardware is failing on .NET 11 but worked on .NET 10, that would suggest .NET 11 did indeed raise the baseline instruction set requirement beyond what .NET 10 needed. Excavator (2015) and later. So hardware from 2012 would have AVX but not AVX2, which would cause this exact failure if .NET 11 raised the baseline to x86-64-v3. Though I'm not entirely certain about the timing—the x86-64-v2 baseline change definitely happened in .NET 9, so the question is whether .NET 11 further bumped it to v3.\n\nGiven the user's scenario fits perfectly with a v3 baseline in .NET 11, that's probably what's happening. I should be straightforward about what I know for certain versus what I'm inferring based on the pattern of .NET raising CPU requirements over time.","outputTokens":1886,"requestId":"A45D:2F4A2A:2314C7D:26D0485:6A03D90E"},"id":"f4f6d74e-49b2-4b32-acff-5d4b5436813c","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:51:49.210Z","parentId":"fc281ee6-02a4-43ec-bcc2-bbe68fa88eea"}
